Tucci]]
([[Chairman]], [[President]] and [[Chief Executive Officer|CEO]]) | industry = [[Computer data storage|Computer storage]] | products = [[EMC Corporation#Products and services|See EMC products]] | revenue = {{nowrap|{{increase}} [[United States dollar|US$]] 21.713 billion (2012){{cite web|url=http://www.sec.gov/Archives/edgar/data/790070/000119312511050151/d10k.htm|title=2010 Form 10-K, EMC Corporation|publisher=United States Securities and Exchange Commission}}}} | operating_income = {{increase}} US$ 3.961 billion (2012) | net_income = {{increase}} US$ 2.732 billion (2012) | assets = {{increase}} US$ 38.068 billion (2012) | equity = {{increase}} US$ 22.357 billion (2012) | num_employees = 60,000 (2012){{cite web|title=Form 10-K, Fiscal Year ended December 31, 2012, EMC Corporation|url=http://www.sec.gov/Archives/edgar/data/790070/000079007013000019/emc-2012123110xk.htm|publisher=SEC.gov}} | subsid = {{ubl|[[VMware]]|[[RSA Security]]|[[Iomega]]}} | homepage = {{url|http://www.emc.com/|emc.com}} }} '''EMC Corporation''' (stylized as '''EMC²''') is an American [[multinational corporation]] that offers [[data storage device|data storage]], [[information security]], [[virtualization]], and [[cloud computing]] products and services which enable businesses to store, manage, protect, and analyze massive volumes of data. EMC's target markets include large FORTUNE 500 companies as well as small business across various vertical markets.{{cite web |url=http://www.hoovers.com/company/EMC_Corporation/rfcsri-1.html |title=EMC Corporation Company Information |publisher=Hoover's |date=2012 |accessdate=February 1, 2013}} It is headquartered in [[Hopkinton, Massachusetts]].Reuters Profile: [http://www.reuters.com/finance/stocks/companyProfile?rpc=66&symbol=EMC EMC CORPORATION (EMC)] Former [[Intel]] executive [[Richard Egan (businessman)|Richard Egan]] and his [[college]] roommate, [[Roger Marino]], founded EMC in 1979. The company’s name, EMC, stands for the initials of the founders, and a third and fourth whose last names are Connelly and Curly hence the EMC^2. As mentioned by Joe Tucci at EMC World 2012 in May 2012, "EMC Corporation" is the company's full name.{{cite web|title=Investor Relations: Frequently Asked Questions|url=http://www.emc.com/about/investor-relations/faqs.htm|publisher=EMC Corporation|accessdate=13 September 2012}} The company's logo also incorporates [[Exponentiation|exponent]] 2, a reference to [[Albert Einstein]]'s [[mass–energy equivalence]] theory. EMC stock [[Initial public offering|went public]] on April 6, 1986, at a price of $16.50 per share.EMC Corporation Announces Two-for-One Stock Split;Annual Meeting of Stockholders, Live Video Web, May 3, 2000, [http://www.allbusiness.com/banking-finance/financial-markets-investing-securities/6434124-1.html D&B AllBusiness] ==History== [[File:Amb. Richard Egan.jpg|thumb|left|Richard Egan, co-founder of EMC Corporation]] EMC, founded in 1979 by [[Richard Egan (businessman)|Richard Egan]] and [[Roger Marino]] (the E and M in EMC),[http://www.emc.com/about/investor-relations/faqs.htm "What does EMC stand for?"] introduced their first 64-kilobyte memory boards for the [[Prime Computer]] in 1981,{{cite news|url=http://www.forbes.com/forbes/2001/1126/062.html|publisher=Forbes|title=What's Eating EMC?|accessdate=2009-07-01|date=November 26, 2001}}{{cite news|url=http://www.forbes.com/forbes/2001/1126/062s01.html|publisher=Forbes|title=Crony Capitalism|accessdate=2009-10-23|date=November 26, 2001}} and continued with the development of memory boards for other computer types. In the mid 1980s the company expanded beyond memory to other [[computer data storage]] types and networked storage platforms. The company started to ship its flagship product, the [[EMC Symmetrix|Symmetrix]] in 1990. The Symmetrix has been developed by a team headed by [[Moshe Yanai]]. This product was the main reason for the rapid growth of EMC in the 1990s, both in size and value, from a company valued hundreds of millions of dollars to a multi-billion company.EMC Company Web site, July 19, 2000 [http://www.emc.com/about/news/press/us/earnings/20000719-469.htm "EMC Reports 43% Growth in Storage Revenue, First $2 Billion Quarter"]. Moshe Yanai managed the Symmetrix development from the product's inception in the late 1980s until shortly before leaving EMC in 2001, and his Symmetrix development team grew from several people to thousands. From 2001, Yanai was named a Founder and EMC Fellow, continuing to serve as a technical strategist.EMC Company Web site, November 29, 2001, [http://www.emc.com/about/news/press/us/2001/20011129-1164.htm "EMC Strengthens Operational Alignment"] EMC remains the largest provider of data storage [[Computing platform|platform]]s in the world, competing with [[IBM]], [[NetApp]], [[Hewlett-Packard]], and [[Hitachi Data Systems]]. Consulting and IT Services have been an increasingly important source of revenue. [[Joseph M. Tucci|Joseph Tucci]], CEO since 2001, was paid over $9 million in 2009.{{cite web|url=http://www.equilar.com/CEO_Compensation/EMC_Joseph_M._Tucci.php|publisher=Equilar|title=Joseph M. Tucci at EMC (EMC) Executive Compensation|accessdate=2010-04-19}} In July 2006 EMC opened a Research and Development office in [[Shanghai, China]], to leverage the burgeoning Chinese labor pool and facilitate a further expansion into the Chinese market.{{cite web|url=http://www.emc.com/news/emc_releases/showRelease.jsp?id=4471|archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20060721154708/http://www.emc.com/news/emc_releases/showRelease.jsp?id=4471|archivedate=2006-07-21|publisher=EMC|title=EMC to Open Software Development Center in China|accessdate=2008-03-26}} On June 7, 2007, EMC announced it was investing $160 million in [[Singapore]] to set up a new {{convert|15000|sqfoot|m2|-2}} development laboratory that would begin operations within the year.http://www.eetasia.com/ART_8800467811_499486_NT_e5b64eb4.HTM A series of acquisitions and partnerships helped grow EMC to the largest provider of data storage platforms in the world. On November 12, 2007, EMC partnered with [[NetQoS]] to deliver the first integrated infrastructure discovery and performance monitoring solutions.{{Clarify|date=April 2011}}{{cite pressrelease|url=http://www.netqos.com/newsroom/press_releases/2007/11-12-07.html|title=NetQoS and EMC Partner to Deliver First Integrated Infrastructure Discovery and Performance Monitoring Solution|publisher=NetQoS|date=November 12, 2007|accessdate=2008-03-26}} ==Products and services== EMC's product line ranges from [[Enterprise storage|enterprise storage arrays]] to [[Enterprise content management|content management systems]] to [[storage area network]]s, [[backup]], [[Data recovery|recovery]] and [[Data_archive#Electronic_archiving|archiving]] solutions and [[information security]]. EMC also offers [[technology consulting]], technology deployment, [[customer service]] and [[Customer support|support]], training, and EMC Proven Professional certification services.D&B AllBusiness Company Profile:[http://www.reuters.com/finance/stocks/companyProfile?symbol=EMC EMC Corporation] {| class="wikitable" |- !
